Introduction

ALEKSCalculus Student Performance Dataset

This dataset contains student performance metrics from the ALEKS (Assessment and Learning in Knowledge Spaces) placement test and their corresponding grades in a Calculus course.

It is designed to analyze:

  • The relationship between math proficiency (ALEKS) and Calculus success.
  • Learning gains across different mathematical topics (post-test vs. pre-test).
  • Differences in performance between students from Mapua SHS vs. external institutions.

Topic Weights (used for both Weighted_Initial and Weighted_Post)

Topic Weight
Algebra & Geometry Review 10%
Graphs & Functions 10%
Polynomial & Rational Functions 20%
Exponential & Logarithmic Functions 10%
Trigonometric Identities & Equations 15%
Systems of Equations & Matrices 20%
Conic Sections 15%

Variable Descriptions

Category Variables Description Range/Values
Target Variable Calculus_Grade Final course grade in Calculus 1.0 (lowest) to 5.0 (highest)
Student Background SHS_Status High school origin 0 = Outside Mapua
1 = Inside Mapua
Initial ALEKS Scores Algebra_Geometry_Initial, Graphs_Functions_Initial, etc. Pre-test scores (7 topics) 0.0 (no mastery) to 1.0 (full mastery)
Post ALEKS Scores Algebra_Geometry_Post, Graphs_Functions_Post, etc. Post-test scores (7 topics) 0.0 to 1.0
Composite Scores Weighted_Initial Weighted aggregate scores (Mitchell 2018 weights) 0.0 to 1.0
Weighted_Post Weighted aggregate scores (Mitchell 2018 weights) 0.0 to 1.0
Improvement Metrics Net_Gain_[Topic] Learning gains (Post Initial) -1.0 (decline) to 1.0 (improvement)

Notes

  • Both Weighted_Initial and Weighted_Post use the same topic weights.
  • Data supports comparative analysis between Mapua SHS and external high school students.

Exploratory Data Analysis

Average Mastery per Topic

Average Initial Mastery per Topic:
- Algebra and Geometry: 0.58
- Graphs and Functions: 0.27
- Polynomial and Rational Functions: 0.07
- Exponential and Logarithmic Functions: 0.31
- Trigonometric Identities and Equations: 0.09
- Systems of Equations and Matrices: 0.06
- Conic Sections: 0.11

The pre-test reveals that the students excel in topics like Algebra and Geometry with an average mastery of 58.27%, on the other hand many of the students struggles with Systems of Equations and Matrices, Trigonometric Identities and Equations, and Polynomial and Rational Functions. The topic where most students fail is Systems of Equations and Matrices with an average mastery of 6.34%

Average Post Mastery per Topic:
- Algebra and Geometry: 0.81
- Graphs and Functions: 0.70
- Polynomial and Rational Functions: 0.56
- Exponential and Logarithmic Functions: 0.78
- Trigonometric Identities and Equations: 0.58
- Systems of Equations and Matrices: 0.25
- Conic Sections: 0.40

The post-test reveals that students had drastically improved their mastery of Mathematical topics after taking the course. The topic with the highest mastery is still Algebra and Geometry review with an average mastery of 81.48%. Students have also made some improvements on the topics they initially struggle with like Trigonometric Identities and Equations and Polynomial and Rational Functions. However, students still struggle with Systems of Equations and Matrices with an average mastery of 25.15%.

Conclusions

  • Initial mastery was weakest in Systems of Equations & Matrices, Polynomial & Rational Functions, and Trigonometry; strongest in Algebra & Geometry.

  • Post-assessment scores jumped across all topics, shifting distributions toward higher mastery; Systems of Equations & Matrices improved but remained the lowest.

  • Weighted Initial vs. Weighted Latest shows a broad upward shift, with many strong improvers from low initial scores.

  • Final Calculus Grade is heavily skewed to 5.0 (fail). That mismatchwith large ALEKS gainssignals misalignment between ALEKS topic mastery and course grading, or assessment design that doesnt reward the specific skills ALEKS builds.

  • Mapa SHS students show a slightly better grade distribution than external SHS students; the effect size looks modest.

  • Using only initial features (and SHS), an early-semester predictive model can flag risk; Weighted Initial Grade is the single most informative feature, with non-linear interactions likely.

  • Data quality is stable (no missing values; duplicates removed), but grade imbalance (many 5.0s) will bias naive models and metrics unless handled explicitly.

Recommendations

  • Early risk flagging: set a data-driven threshold on Weighted Initial (e.g., bottom quartile or pass/fail Youden cutoff) for automatic alerts in week 12.

  • Targeted remediation: prioritize Systems of Equations & Matrices, then Polynomial/Rational and Trig; provide problem sets mirroring Calculus exam formats, not just ALEKS item styles.

  • Assessment alignment: map ALEKS competencies to Calculus learning outcomes; add bridging tasks (multi-step word problems, algebra-to-calculus translation, proof-lite reasoning) so mastery transfers to exams.

  • Instructional pacing: introduce matrix methods and function manipulation earlier, with spaced retrieval and cumulative quizzes to keep skills from decaying.

  • Program support: pre-semester bootcamp for low initial scores; mandatory mastery checkpoints tied to tutoring/office hours before major exams.

  • Modeling pipeline upgrades: treat grade as ordinal or cast to pass/fail for operational use; use cross-validation, imbalance-aware metrics, and calibration; report MAE/RMSE/R for regression plus ordinal metrics; add SHAP to surface which topics drive risk per student.

  • Fairness checks: monitor error and intervention rates by SHS group; ensure the model doesnt systematically over- or under-flag external students.

  • Data operations: keep a versioned data dictionary, continue duplicate suppression, and verify the grading scale semantics (confirm 5.0 = fail) each term; re-evaluate thresholds every cohort.
